\h 2 Corinthians
\mt The Second Epistle of Paul the Apostle to the Corinthians 
\c 1
\p
\v 1 Paul, an apostle of Jesus Christ by the will of God, and Timothy 
\add our\add* brother, unto the church of God which is at Corinth, with all
the saints which are in all Achaia: 
\v 2 Grace be to you and peace from God our Father, and \add from\add* the
Lord Jesus Christ. 
\v 3 Blessed \add be\add* God, even the Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, the
Father of mercies, and the God of all comfort; 
\v 4 Who comforteth us in all our tribulation, that we may be able to comfort
them which are in any trouble, by the comfort wherewith we ourselves are
comforted of God. 
\v 5 For as the sufferings of Christ abound in us, so our consolation also
aboundeth by Christ. 
\v 6 And whether we be afflicted, \add it is\add* for your consolation and
salvation, which is effectual in the enduring of the same sufferings which we
also suffer: or whether we be comforted, \add it is\add* for your consolation
and salvation. 
\v 7 And our hope of you \add is\add* stedfast, knowing, that as ye are
partakers of the sufferings, so \add shall ye be\add* also of the
consolation. 
\v 8 For we would not, brethren, have you ignorant of our trouble which came
to us in Asia, that we were pressed out of measure, above strength, insomuch
that we despaired even of life: 
\v 9 But we had the sentence of death in ourselves, that we should not trust
in ourselves, but in God which raiseth the dead: 
\v 10 Who delivered us from so great a death, and doth deliver: in whom we
trust that he will yet deliver \add us; \add*
\v 11 Ye also helping together by prayer for us, that for the gift \add bestowed
\add* upon us by the means of many persons thanks may be given by many on our
behalf.
\p
\v 12 For our rejoicing is this, the testimony of our conscience, that in
simplicity and godly sincerity, not with fleshly wisdom, but by the grace of
God, we have had our conversation in the world, and more abundantly to
you-ward. 
\v 13 For we write none other things unto you, than what ye read or
acknowledge; and I trust ye shall acknowledge even to the end; 
\v 14 As also ye have acknowledged us in part, that we are your rejoicing,
even as ye also \add are\add* ours in the day of the Lord Jesus.
\p
\v 15 And in this confidence I was minded to come unto you before, that ye
might have a second benefit; 
\v 16 And to pass by you into Macedonia, and to come again out of Macedonia
unto you, and of you to be brought on my way toward Judaea. 
\v 17 When I therefore was thus minded, did I use lightness? or the things
that I purpose, do I purpose according to the flesh, that with me there should
be yea yea, and nay nay? 
\v 18 But \add as\add* God \add is\add* true, our word toward you was not yea
and nay. 
\v 19 For the Son of God, Jesus Christ, who was preached among you by us, 
\add even\add* by me and Silvanus and Timotheus, was not yea and nay, but in
him was yea. 
\v 20 For all the promises of God in him \add are\add* yea, and in him Amen,
unto the glory of God by us. 
\v 21 Now he which stablisheth us with you in Christ, and hath anointed us, 
\add is\add* God; 
\v 22 Who hath also sealed us, and given the earnest of the Spirit in our
hearts. 
\v 23 Moreover I call God for a record upon my soul, that to spare you I came
not as yet unto Corinth. 
\v 24 Not for that we have dominion over your faith, but are helpers of your
joy: for by faith ye stand.
\c 2
\p
\v 1 But I determined this with myself, that I would not come again to you in
heaviness. 
\v 2 For if I make you sorry, who is he then that maketh me glad, but the same
which is made sorry by me? 
\v 3 And I wrote this same unto you, lest, when I came, I should have sorrow
from them of whom I ought to rejoice; having confidence in you all, that my
joy is \add the joy\add* of you all. 
\v 4 For out of much affliction and anguish of heart I wrote unto you with
many tears; not that ye should be grieved, but that ye might know the love
which I have more abundantly unto you. 
\v 5 But if any have caused grief, he hath not grieved me, but in part: that I
may not overcharge you all. 
\v 6 Sufficient to such a man is this punishment, which \add was inflicted
\add* of many. 
\v 7 So that contrariwise ye \add ought\add* rather to forgive \add him,
\add* and comfort \add him,\add* lest perhaps such a one should be swallowed
up with overmuch sorrow. 
\v 8 Wherefore I beseech you that ye would confirm \add your\add* love toward
him. 
\v 9 For to this end also did I write, that I might know the proof of you,
whether ye be obedient in all things. 
\v 10 To whom ye forgive any thing, I \add forgive\add* also: for if I forgave
any thing, to whom I forgave \add it,\add* for your sakes \add forgave I it
\add* in the person of Christ; 
\v 11 Lest Satan should get an advantage of us: for we are not ignorant of his
devices. 
\v 12 Furthermore, when I came to Troas to \add preach\add* Christ’s gospel,
and a door was opened unto me of the Lord, 
\v 13 I had no rest in my spirit, because I found not Titus my brother: but
taking my leave of them, I went from thence into Macedonia. 
\v 14 Now thanks \add be\add* unto God, which always causeth us to triumph in
Christ, and maketh manifest the savour of his knowledge by us in every place.
\v 15 For we are unto God a sweet savour of Christ, in them that are saved,
and in them that perish: 
\v 16 To the one \add we are\add* the savour of death unto death; and to the
other the savour of life unto life. And who \add is\add* sufficient for these
things? 
\v 17 For we are not as many, which corrupt the word of God: but as of
sincerity, but as of God, in the sight of God speak we in Christ.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 Do we begin again to commend ourselves? or need we, as some \add others,
\add* epistles of commendation to you, or \add letters\add* of commendation
from you? 
\v 2 Ye are our epistle written in our hearts, known and read of all men: 
\v 3 \add Forasmuch as ye are\add* manifestly declared to be the epistle of
Christ ministered by us, written not with ink, but with the Spirit of the
living God; not in tables of stone, but in fleshy tables of the heart.
\p
\v 4 And such trust have we through Christ to God-ward: 
\v 5 Not that we are sufficient of ourselves to think any thing as of
ourselves; but our sufficiency \add is\add* of God; 
\v 6 Who also hath made us able ministers of the new testament; not of the
letter, but of the spirit: for the letter killeth, but the spirit giveth
life. 
\v 7 But if the ministration of death, written \add and\add* engraven in
stones, was glorious, so that the children of Israel could not stedfastly
behold the face of Moses for the glory of his countenance; which \add glory
\add* was to be done away: 
\v 8 How shall not the ministration of the spirit be rather glorious? 
\v 9 For if the ministration of condemnation \add be\add* glory, much more
doth the ministration of righteousness exceed in glory. 
\v 10 For even that which was made glorious had no glory in this respect, by
reason of the glory that excelleth. 
\v 11 For if that which is done away \add was\add* glorious, much more that
which remaineth \add is\add* glorious. 
\v 12 Seeing then that we have such hope, we use great plainness of speech: 
\v 13 And not as Moses, \add which\add* put a vail over his face, that the
children of Israel could not stedfastly look to the end of that which is
